observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Local Chief Executive (LCE):
Require the Municipal Engineering Office (MEO) to provide the concerned offices, the GSO, Inventory Committee, and Municipal Accounting Office (MAccO), of available records pertaining to local road networks with complete description and cost segregation to enable reconciliation of respective existing records and, prospectively, to facilitate the preparation of required reports and records in the format prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-008;
Direct the GSO to prepare and maintain the Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components, including Road Map. Moreover, ensure that the Report on Local Road Network be prepared by the GSO at the end of accounting period;
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of its road networks in order to ascertain the existence of the balance of the account Road Networks;
Require the GSO and Inventory Committee with the MAccO to reconcile their reports and records to ensure the fair presentation of the Road Networks account in the FS; and
Require the MAccO to adequately provide the required disclosure pertaining to Road Networks in the Notes to FS.

We recommended that the Office of the Municipal Treasurer:
Require each AOs (the Collectors and the MT) to prepare and submit individual RAAFs;
Ensure that consolidated RAAF resulted from the consolidation of all the AOs’ individual RAAFs;
Require the MT to ensure inclusion of checks in his individual RAAF and, accordingly, in the consolidated RAAF; and
Ensure preparation and submission of these RAAFs in accordance with the cited regulations.

We recommended that the Office of the Municipal Treasurer:
Ensure that additional CAs are drawn only after the liquidation of previous CAs;
Strictly and religiously monitor the submission of Liquidation Reports/Report of Disbursements for the timely accounting thereof in order to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances;
Warrant the enhancement of the reconciliation of records in order to avoid omission of transactions pertaining to cash advances and liquidation;
Reevaluate existing conditions and consider designation of additional DO, when warranted, to facilitate prompt liquidation of CAs, likewise, ensuring that all cash advance and liquidation transactions are completely recorded in the Cashbook; and
Ensure compliance with existing laws, rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of CAs.

We recommended that Management:

Determine the nature of the noted variances;

Effect immediately the necessary adjusting entries to reflect the correct account balances of the RPT/SET Receivables and the corresponding Deferred RPT/SET Income accounts;

Ensure the propriety of the JEV drawn at the beginning of the year to establish the RPT/SET Receivables and its corresponding Deferred RPT/SET Income accounts;

Warrant the timely submission of the RCDs with copies of ORs and validated deposit slips to the Municipal Accounting Office. Likewise, ensure the prompt correction of the discrepancies and reconciliation of the variances or differences, as the same arises; and 

Prospectively, ensure strict adherence with the pro-forma journal entries provided in the MNGAS to avoid discrepancies/differences/variances in the balances of the accounts.

We recommended the Management to: 	

Revisit the status of outstanding checks to determine whether they are still in the custody of the cashier or in the hands of the payee; 

Replace with new checks the stale checks that are in the hands of the payee, upon compliance with the required procedures; 

Ensure that checks, when not claimed and remained in the custody of the Municipal Treasurer be attached to the original voucher and prepare a Schedule of Unreleased Check for submission to the Accounting office at year-end; and


Install a monitoring mechanism that will facilitate notification to payees or holder of checks issued one month prior to the date when issued checks will become stale so that concerned payees will be aware of the depository bank’s action on these issued checks six months after the date of its issuance.

We recommended the Management through the MDRRMO to:

Evaluate the unutilized balances of the current year’s five per cent LDRRMF, continuing LDRRMF, and the unexpended LDRRMF transferred to the TF books and take appropriate actions relative thereto;


Anticipate and promptly address issues and concerns affecting the efficient and effective implementation of LDRRM PPAs to avoid delays or non-implementation;

Enhance LDRRMF utilization focusing on PPAs requiring the highest priority in terms of urgency and/or impact on the four thematic areas of Disaster Risk Reduction and Management and considering the needs of the time such as the COVID-19 emergency; and

Ensure efficient and effective implementation of all programmed and reprogrammed projects during the budget year to optimize the utilization of the fund and to warrant that goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities be achieved.

We recommended that Management:

Ensure the full implementation of all the identified priority projects funded under SEF;



Follow the Calendar Schedule for the preparation of the SEF budget in accordance to Section 5.5 of DEPED-DBM-DILG JC No. 1 series of 2017;

Install regular monitoring mechanism to assess the progress of project implementation so that all its programmed projects could be implemented immediately to ensure that intended beneficiaries avail of the maximum benefits that will be derived therefrom; and

Ensure that Program of Works (POW), detailed engineering and other pre-procurement activities on the proposed infrastructure projects under the SEF be promptly conducted for the early procurement and on-time implementation thereof.

We recommended that Management:
Determine the nature of the noted variances;
Effect immediately the necessary adjusting entries to reflect the correct account balances of the RPT/SET Receivables and the corresponding Deferred RPT/SET Income accounts;
Ensure the propriety of the JEV drawn at the beginning of the year to establish the RPT/SET Receivables and its corresponding Deferred RPT/SET Income accounts;
Warrant the timely submission of the RCDs with copies of ORs and validated deposit slips to the Municipal Accounting Office. Likewise, ensure the prompt correction of the discrepancies and reconciliation of the variances or differences, as the same arises; and
Prospectively, ensure strict adherence with the pro-forma journal entries provided in the MNGAS to avoid discrepancies/differences/variances in the balances of the accounts.

We recommended that Management:
Revisit the status of outstanding checks to determine whether they are still in the custody of the cashier or in the hands of the payee;
Replace with new checks the stale checks that are in the hands of the payee, upon compliance with the required procedures;
Ensure that checks, when not claimed and remained in the custody of the Municipal Treasurer be attached to the original voucher and prepare a Schedule of Unreleased Check for submission to the Accounting office at year-end; and
Install a monitoring mechanism that will facilitate notification to payees or holder of checks issued one month prior to the date when issued checks will become stale so that concerned payees will be aware of the depository bank’s action on these issued checks six months after the date of its issuance.

We recommended that Management, through the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (MDRRMO) to:
Evaluate the unutilized balances of the current year’s five per cent LDRRMF, continuing LDRRMF, and the unexpended LDRRMF transferred to the TF books and take appropriate actions relative thereto;
Anticipate and promptly address issues and concerns affecting the efficient and effective implementation of LDRRM PPAs to avoid delays or non-implementation;
Enhance LDRRMF utilization focusing on PPAs requiring the highest priority in terms of urgency and/or impact on the four thematic areas of Disaster Risk Reduction and Management and considering the needs of the time such as the COVID-19 emergency; and
Ensure efficient and effective implementation of all programmed and reprogrammed projects during the budget year to optimize the utilization of the fund and to warrant that goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities be achieved.

We recommended that Management takes the following courses of actions:

Direct the officials concerned to ensure that the 20 per cent of the IRA is optimally utilized in the prompt implementation of programs and projects to achieve the desirable socio-economic development and as prescribed by existing regulations;
Properly plan and prioritize projects/programs/activities under the 20 per cent DF so as to attain fully the purpose of the fund; 

Re-appropriate the funds of PPAs which have become irrelevant or not responsive to current priority undertakings; and 
Inasmuch as funds were already disbursed under the 20 per cent DF, effect the transfer of the constructed asset upon its completion to the DEPED in accordance with the PPSAS.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of actions:
Create an Inventory Committee to facilitate the conduct of annual physical inventory of PPE;
Perform periodic reconciliation of property cards to ensure that all discrepancies are immediately investigated, cleared and reconciled with the books of accounts;
Reclassify to the proper inventory accounts tangible assets small enough to be considered as PPE reported in the RPCPPE; and
Continuously analyze the reconciling items in the PPE account and accordingly adjust the books of accounts and the property records, if warranted.

We recommended that Management:
Ensure the full implementation of all the identified priority projects funded under SEF;
Follow the Calendar Schedule for the preparation of the SEF budget in accordance to Section 5.5 of DEPED-DBM-DILG JC No. 1 series of 2017;
Install regular monitoring mechanism to assess the progress of project implementation so that all its programmed projects could be implemented immediately to ensure that intended beneficiaries avail of the maximum benefits that will be derived therefrom; and
Ensure that POW, detailed engineering and other pre-procurement activities on the proposed infrastructure projects under the SEF be promptly conducted for the early procurement and on-time implementation thereof.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

Strictly adhere to the above-cited laws, rules and regulations;









Instruct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to immediately submit the subject 1,049 DVs together with its complete supporting documents;




Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to ensure that paid DVs are intact as listed in the RCI upon transmittal to the Office of the Accountant; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to always transmit complete submission of accounts to facilitate thorough audit and verification of the agency’s financial transactions.

We recommended that Management:

Follow the Calendar Schedule for the preparation of Gender and Development Plan and Budget (GPB) for LGUs and incorporate the DILG-approved/endorsed GPB in the Annual Budget to ensure that the programs, projects and activities reflected thereat are in accordance with the existing regulations and guidelines;
Submit annual Gender and Development (GAD) Accomplishment Report (AR) accompanied by the required documents specified in the above-cited provisions;
Set-up and maintain GAD database as spearheaded by the Local Planning and Development Officer (LPDO) that will serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation; and
Follow Philippine Commission on Women (PCW)-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended by JMC No. 2016-01 to fully address and implement applicable provisions in the convention on the elimination of all forms of discrimination against women and promote gender equality within the Municipality.
